The two notes describe the same patient's case with some differences in detail and focus. Both notes mention the patient's complaint of right shoulder pain, its duration, and its impact on daily activities and sleep. They also both reference the history of a painless snap during sports activity 11 years ago and the absence of relevant family or medical history.

The first note provides a detailed account of the patient's surgical procedure, postoperative course, and long-term follow-up, including specific surgical findings and histological examination results. It also includes detailed imaging findings and the final diagnosis of a solitary osteochondroma (OC) with a large bursa.

The second note is more concise, focusing on the initial presentation, physical examination findings, and imaging results. It mentions the suspicion of a malignant bone tumor and the plan for further examination and biopsy but does not include surgical details or long-term follow-up.

Overall, the notes are similar in describing the patient's condition and initial assessment but differ in the level of detail and the aspects of the case they emphasize.
